<subSubSection id="278B962A10A5C80CD3D7DAA53AC958DA" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" type="notes on the genus">
<paragraph id="A7EBB8D2915177E8AFA9DFEDCD520C9D" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">Notes on the genus.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7E5D4B572BB427A1D8FD6F3231848C11" pageId="1" pageNumber="22">
The diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName id="736EB55F35486BD727AD57B076CE17A8" authority="Berlese, 1902" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1902" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" genus="Myrmozercon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myrmozercon" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Myrmozercon</taxonomicName>
used here is based on that of 
<bibRefCitation id="5CCBA578921838584B1AABC7454A6480" author="Shaw, MD" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" pagination="43 - 55" title="Two new species of Myrmozercon (Acari: Laelapidae) from Australian ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae)." volume="2025" year="2009">Shaw and Seeman (2009)</bibRefCitation>
. Most species of 
<taxonomicName id="6A1308EED4D08AB99BB66D27D41FB5DA" authority="Berlese, 1902" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1902" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" genus="Myrmozercon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myrmozercon" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Myrmozercon</taxonomicName>
, including the type species 
<taxonomicName id="986EEB7ABCB925FBB5D3C73D88629633" authority="Berlese, 1902" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1902" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" genus="Myrmozercon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myrmozercon brevipes" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipes">Myrmozercon brevipes</taxonomicName>
, show moderate to strong hypertrichy on the dorsal shield. However, 
<taxonomicName id="61C2DBC076B2CC4D929A150741653CED" authority="Berlese, 1902" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1902" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" genus="Myrmozercon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myrmozercon burwelli" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burwelli">Myrmozercon burwelli</taxonomicName>
Shaw &amp; Seeman, 2009 (24-25 pairs), and the new species, have a reduced dorsal chaetotaxy. All species appear to have asymmetrical and unpaired setae on the dorsal shield, which makes it difficult to recognise their homology except the new species. In most species the dorsal shield is reduced or truncated posteriorly to expose a strip of unsclerotised opisthonotal skin, but this is not true for every species. Species of 
<taxonomicName id="FCAFB1A9461CA3DD14362F2E9776ED86" authority="Berlese, 1902" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1902" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" genus="Myrmozercon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myrmozercon" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Myrmozercon</taxonomicName>
also vary in the presence or absence of metasternal setae st4, the sternal shield of new species is extended to which the sternal shield is fused with the endopodal plates, with three pairs of setae and three pairs of lyrifissures and metasternal setae (st4) absent. The leg chaetotaxy of 
<taxonomicName id="C233D3877AAEB3BC3A3BBF79921CDD6B" authority="Berlese, 1902" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1902" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" genus="Myrmozercon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myrmozercon" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Myrmozercon</taxonomicName>
species is variable, and does not provide diagnostic characters that define the genus (
<bibRefCitation id="8E0A5714D852A5D7733D96939ABC6D5D" author="Shaw, MD" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" pagination="43 - 55" title="Two new species of Myrmozercon (Acari: Laelapidae) from Australian ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae)." volume="2025" year="2009">Shaw and Seeman 2009</bibRefCitation>
) and this is very characteristic and fixed in the new species. The new species has one ventral seta on the palp trochanter the same as in most species of 
<taxonomicName id="2EBC9B40D5E13B09C095412AB0BEC363" authority="Berlese, 1902" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1902" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" genus="Myrmozercon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myrmozercon" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Myrmozercon</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="3A5F37DB57E01E3AA1625959241E125F" author="Shaw, MD" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" pagination="43 - 55" title="Two new species of Myrmozercon (Acari: Laelapidae) from Australian ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae)." volume="2025" year="2009">Shaw and Seeman (2009)</bibRefCitation>
described a swelling on the dorso-distal edge of the palp trochanter in several species, but this structure is not present in new species. This instability in morphology, and the edentate chelicerae and short peritremes of 
<taxonomicName id="DD15600BCC2F0395F9BE516D5B731C24" authority="Berlese, 1902" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1902" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" genus="Myrmozercon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myrmozercon" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Myrmozercon</taxonomicName>
, suggest that 
<taxonomicName id="76351496CBA740D26B21B4FC6A69BB32" authority="Berlese, 1902" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1902" class="Arachnida" family="Laelapidae" genus="Myrmozercon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myrmozercon" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="1" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Myrmozercon</taxonomicName>
is parasitic on its ant hosts, and not simply a commensal in its 
<normalizedToken id="63860E510EF77DF53F8F38D9F99CB8D8" originalValue="host’s">host's</normalizedToken>
nests, but this has not been established experimentally. The specimens of new specieswere found clinging to the abdomen and head of the ants.
</paragraph>
